parameters.name: BCCompletionState
parameters.description: The business case completion state.

parameters.name: ID
parameters.description: ID refers to a Workfront Object ID. You can use a unique Project ID to access a particular project, or you can locate a Project that is associated with a different object, like a Task, by entering that object's unique ID into a project query.

parameters.name: URL
parameters.description: This refers to the Uniform Resource Location of an object or endpoint. You can access a particular project by using its unique URL, locate a project associated with a different object by including its URL in a Project Query, or make changes to objects associated with a project by including their URLs in certain types of requests.

parameters.name: actualBenefit
parameters.description: The actual financial benefit that was gained upon completion of an object or group of objects, such as Tasks.

parameters.name: actualCompletionDate
parameters.description: The Actual Completion Date represents the real date and time a duration-measured object, such as a Task or Project, are maked as completed.

parameters.name: actualCost
parameters.description:
Reperesents the Actual Costs that were accumulated prior to the completion of a duration-measured object, like a Task or Project.
The Actual Cost of a Project is calculated by: Actual Labor Cost of all Tasks + Actual Expense Cost of all Tasks + Actual Labor Cost of the Project + Actual Expense Cost of the Project.

parameters.name: actualDurationMinutes
parameters.description: The difference, in minutes, between the Actual Start Date and the Actual Completion Date of a duration-measured object. In other words, this is how long a Task, Project, or other duration-measured object actually took to complete, in minutes.

parameters.name: actualExpenseCost
parameters.description: Actual Expense Cost is the final cost of expenses that has accumulated at the completion of an object, like a project, or a group of objects, such as Tasks. The Actual Expense Cost of a project is the final total of expense costs accumulated by the completion of a Project.

parameters.name: actualLaborCost
parameters.description: Actual Labor Cost is the final labor cost that has accumulated at the completion of an object, like a project, or a group of objects, such as Tasks. The Actual Labor Cost of a Project is the final total of Labor Costs that accumulated by the completion of a project.

parameters.name: actualRevenue
parameters.description:
Actual Revenue is the revenue associated with the Actual Hours of Tasks. That is, the revenue associated with the Actual Hours of the tasks becomes the Actual Revenue.
For example, if a task with User Hourly Revenue Type is planned to take 2 hours and the user assigned to it has an hourly rate of $30 an hour, then the Planned Revenue of the task is $60. When the task is completed, if the user logs just 1.5 hours as the actual time spent to finish the task, the Actual Revenue amount is $45

parameters.name: actualRiskCost
parameters.description: Actual Risk Cost is the Actual Cost value that was assigned to a Risk object. The Actual Risk Cost of a Project is a summation of the Actual Costs associated with all the Risk objects that were specified on a project.

parameters.name: actualStartDate
parameters.description: Actual Start Date is the actual date that work begins on a Project, Task, or Issue object. That is, the Actual Start Date of a project, task, or issue is not populated when these items are created. The Actual Start Date is populated when work actually starts on a project, task, or issue.

parameters.name: actualValue
parameters.description: Actual Value

parameters.name: actualWorkRequired
parameters.description:
Work Required is the duration of Task hours multiplied by the number of resources assigned to that task. Actual work required is a summation of these values at the completion of a project. The formula looks something like:
Actual Work Required = SUM(Duration of the task in hours) x (Percent allocated towards tasks for each resource).

parameters.name: alignment
parameters.description: Alignment is a reference to the Alignment Score that is generated after a Score Card is completed for a project. A Project Alignment Score = The sum of the question points from the scorecard met at a given time/ The sum of the possible points on the scorecard. The Portfolio Alignment Score = The sum of the percentages of the project alignment scores/ Number of projects in the portfolio. If a project does not have a scorecard associated with it, and therefore it does not have an alignment score, it is considered to have a 0% alignment in the portfolio. The project is taken into account in the number of projects in the portfolio.

parameters.name: alignmentScoreCardID
parameters.description: Alignment Scorecard ID refers to the unique ID that is assigned to a Score Card. An Alignment Scorecard ID is directly related to the project for which the Scorecard was created.

parameters.name: auditTypes
parameters.description: Audits are system messages that record actions occuring in a Workfront environment. The following audit types are recorded: Scope Change, Attachment Action, General Edit, Status Change, Note, Combined Entry, Error Entry, Status Change, Subscription Change

parameters.name: autoBaselineRecurOn
parameters.description: The baseline is a project snapshot that represents key pieces of data included in the initial project plan as approved prior to execution. A baseline is used to compare those data points from the current plan to the original plan to identify problem tasks, scope creep, and other trends over time. Auto Baseline Recur On can be set so a baseline is automatically created on projects.

parameters.name: budgetedCost
parameters.description:
The Budgeted Cost for the project is calculated using the following formula:
Budgeted Cost = Budgeted Expense Cost + Budgeted Labor Cost + Fixed Cost of the project

parameters.name: budgetedHours
parameters.description: These are the hours that are budgeted for your resources to complete work on a Project. This field refers to both hours budgeted in the Legacy Resource Estimates area of a project (or in the Capacity Planner), and hours budgeted in the Resource Budgeting area of the Business Case (or in the Resource Planner)

parameters.name: budgetedLaborCost
parameters.description:
This is the cost associated with the hours that are budgeted for your resources to complete work on Projects. The Budgeted Labor Cost in a project report is calculated using the following formula:
Budgeted Labor Cost = SUM(Job Role Cost per Hour * Budgeted Hours per Job Role)
This field refers to both labor costs for hours budgeted in the Legacy Resource Estimates area of a project (or in the Capacity Planner), and hours budgeted in the Resource Budgeting area of the Business Case (or in the Resource Planner).

parameters.name: budgetedStartDate
parameters.description: This is a deprecated field that shows the date when the budgeting of resources starts, as defined in the Legacy Resource Estimates area of the Business Case of a project, or the Capacity Planner. The field is available in project and task reports.

parameters.name: categoryID
parameters.description: A category is a custom form. You can build reports for this object and you can show it in other object reports, as well. A category ID is a unique ID that is assigned to a category at its creation. Not all objects can have a custom form, or category. The following objects can have a custom form: Project, Task, Issue, Portfolio, Document, Expense, Program, User, Company

parameters.name: cpi
parameters.description: The Cost Performance Index (CPI) describes the relationship (at the project or task level) between the planned cost and actual cost. Project Managers review this metric to identify tasks or projects currently tracking under or over cost at a given point. Cost can be measured in hours or dollars, depending on your Performance Index Method (PIM). For additional information about CPI, including how it is calculated under different circumstances, please visit the Workfront Experience CPI help article.

parameters.name: csi
parameters.description: The Cost Schedule Performance Index (CSI) is an automatic calculation which combines the Cost Performance Index (CPI) and Schedule Performance Index (SPI) into one general metric that balances cost and schedule. By multiplying these values together, a single metric can account for a protracted schedule at a lower budget or vice versa. Project managers may use this to determine general project or task health when cost is sacrificed to drive schedule mid-project. For additional information about CSI, please visit the Workfront Experience CSI help article.

parameters.name: currency
parameters.description: Project Managers and other users can configure a project to use a currency other than the default currency. This allows you to display financial information on your project in the desired currency when calculating labor costs and revenue. For additional information about currency, please visit the Workfront Experience Default Currency help article.

parameters.name: enableAutoBaselines
parameters.description: The baseline is a project snapshot that represents key pieces of data included in the initial project plan as approved prior to execution. A baseline is used to compare those data points from the current plan to the original plan to identify problem tasks, scope creep, and other trends over time. When Enable Auto Baselines is enabled, Workfront automatically creates a baseline (snapshot) of task and project details when the status of the project changes to Current.
